entry.content:
The bridge only connects to native so far. Since there is no real

showing/dismissing happening, any call leads to a dismissal so that

using the bridge would be save already since clean-up is guaranteed.



The bridge accepts context and bottomsheet controller (for the

view). All passed objects are weak since they may be invalidated

by the time they are needed. A null dependency is equivalent to

an invalidated dependency.

Passing them as weak ensures that the construction always succeeds

and never fails to create a java-bridge.

The coordinator/mediator can then handle the absence of a

dependency (spoiler: it will do nothing but still ensure the proper

clean-up ... but this logic doesn't belong in the bridge.)

entry.title: Fix race condition in a few tests in URLLoaderTest
entry.content:
This is the same race condition that was earlier patched in

URLLoaderTest.ClientAuthCertificateWith(Invalid|Valid)Signature. See CL

referenced.



This patch fixes a race condition within the URLLoader gtests that

causes tests to fail. Sometimes url_loader is nullptr and sometimes

certificates has been requested even though the test expects different.



The reason for this race condition relates to the usage of

RunLoop::RunUntilIdle. Before, the test did the following:



1. The tests creates an URLLoader that requests a resource from

EmbeddedTestServer.

2. The test does RunLoop::RunUntilIdle

3. The test checks that URLLoader has not been deleted, which is made

upon request completion.



Most of the times, this succeeds. Sometimes it does not, mostly on

slower systems or on systems under heavy load. I think the reason is

that the test makes an incorrect assumption with regards to

RunLoop::RunUntilIdle and how threads are scheduled on an OS. What I

think happens is:



1. The network request to EmbeddedTestServer is made from the test main

thread.

2. The OS can context switch away from the test main thread before the

task system has reached an idle state.

3. The IO thread of EmbeddedTestServer responds to the request made by

URLLoader.

4. When the test thread is again scheduled, it has new data to fetch

from the server, triggering new tasks and completing the URL load.

This causes the checks that no progress on the URL request has been

made to fail.



This patch removes checks for temporary state that cannot be guaranteed

within the tests and instead makes the tests solely rely on expected

end-state, for which there's no race condition.

all layout types.

entry.title: [cc/tiles] Fix transfer cache entry deletion in GpuImageDecodeCache
entry.content:
The renderer-side GpuImageDecodeCache is referencing GPU process side

memory in the transfer cache. When memory is deleted from it, the

deletion can actually happen much later, since the delete command may

sit in a buffer. A previous commit

(https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4704673)

added a "flush" call to make sure that the deletion makes its way to the

GPU process even when no outside event forces it (e.g. a frame commit,

or other memory reclaim action). However, it doesn't work, because it

only flushes "deferred messages" (see GpuChannelHost::InternalFlush()),

but transfer cache entry deletion is a regular command buffer command

(see DeleteTransferCacheEntryINTERNAL()).



This means that we need a shallow command buffer flush to ensure that

deletion commands are actually processed. This has been a longstanding

bug in (at least) GpuImageDecodeCache, impacting

GpuImageDecodeCache::ClearCache() (and its callers), in particular

memory pressure signals processing.



Locally, loading a static page with lots of images, we observe that

prior to this commit, >200MiB can be used by the transfer cache, and not

go away as planned until a new frame is produced. On an ARM64 mac

laptop, this is verified with IOAccelerator memory, which is backing

transfer cache memory GPU-side.



$ vmmap $GPU_PROCESS_PID

[...]

VIRTUAL RESIDENT DIRTY SWAPPED VOLATILE NONVOL EMPTY REGION

REGION TYPE SIZE SIZE SIZE SIZE SIZE SIZE SIZE COUNT (non-coalesced)

=========== ======= ======== ===== ======= ======== ====== ===== =======

[...]

IOAccelerator 22.4M 112K 112K 6880K 0K 0K 15.4M 198

This CL introduces a mechanism to reset non-eager prerenders, allowing

them to be retriggered after they have been canceled due to a limit.



To realize this, PrerenderHostRegistry notifies PrerendererImpl of

cancellation via Observer, and PrerendererImpl notifies

PreloadingDecider of it via callback. Upon receiving notification, they

reset their state respectively.



For more information, please see the design doc:

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1y6SmftZ2B3IXt3cq3CIc2LZUylcIzy63clGSwJszqPc

entry.title: Move dropped frames counters from source to track.
entry.content:
If a cloned track has a different FPS than the original track we'll end

up with two VideoTrackAdapters with their own instance of the frame

decimation algorithm running. This means that a frame that was discarded

by one VTA may not be discarded by the other VTA - or it may even be

discarded by both VTAs - which all results in

MediaStreamVideoSource::OnFrameDropped() independently of other VTAs.



This meant that a clone could cause the source discarded counters to go

up, which showed up in the original track's getFrameStats() results

since both tracks are backed by the same source.



To fix this, the track stats are moved from per-source to per-track,

specifically to MediaStreamVideoTrack's FrameDeliverer. This means:

- All frame counters now live in the same place, on the same thread and

map 1:1 to a single track. Simpler and no per-frame PostTask needed.

- The code in MediaStreamTrackImpl that was previously needed to convert

per-source counters to per-track counters can be deleted.



WPT coverage for this is added and other tests moved.

entry.title: [Link Capturing] Allow link capturing while in a web app window
entry.content:
We currently block link capturing while in a web app window. This blocks

link capturing from target="_self" links, but still allows it from

target="_blank". We want to make this consistent and always allow link

capturing between web apps, regardless of the link type.



The tricky part here is handling middle-clicks correctly. This CL

maintains the existing Browser based logic, but reintroduces the

layering violation of //c/b/apps depending on //c/b/ui, which would need

to be resolved long-term.

entry.title: Stop storing Print Preview request data in PrintPreviewUI
entry.content:
Since the Print Preview UI can be reloaded in some rare cases, the

PrintPreviewUI instance that runs the UI can get destroyed and

recreated. If this happens, PrintPreviewUI will lose track of some

values and hand out potentially incorrect values.



Prevent this situation from happening by storing the Print Preview

request data in PrintPreviewDialogController instead. Divert all data

getters/setters to use the new data source. PrintPreviewDialogController

already keeps track of all print preview requests, and it is immune to

Print Preview UI reloads.



To keep the existing PrintPreviewHandlerTest working, add some test-only

calls to (dis)associate WebContentses, as the test manually creates its

own.



To keep tests that navigate directly to chrome://print working, allow

PrintPreviewHandler to use dummy request data when

PrintPreviewDialogController does not know about the Print Preview.



Do some cleanups along the way, to tidy things up. In particular,

avoid including Print Preview headers when Print Preview is not

available.
